#let metadata = (
  title: "Flight Preparation and Ground Operations",
  unit: "Group A (3-Axis) | Phase 1 — Lesson 0 | E1",
  author: "C.Moroney",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Flight Preparation and Ground Operations]

,aim: [
Complete a pre-flight sequence — aircraft documentation and inspection — and develop the theoretical foundation for the first flight, effects of controls. Review the training process, and become familiar with the grading and assessment systems used at GCSFT.
]

,overview: [
Lesson 0 is a ground-only lesson and the student's first formal contact with the training syllabus. No flight is conducted. The lesson covers everything the student needs to know before they fly for the first time: the documents required for the flight, the preflight inspection procedure, how to read the maintenance release, how to inspect the aircraft, and how to assess their own fitness to fly. They will also learn the theory knowledge required for their first lesson — axes of movement, stability, controls and their effects. Finally, the training syllabus is also introduced: the expectations of the student, how they progress through the training syllabus, the assessments and grading system that will be used.

Delivering this content on the ground, without the competing demands of the flight, gives the student a proper foundation and ensures Lesson 1 is focused entirely on flying. At the end of the lesson, the student sits in the cockpit for familiarisation only — identifying controls and instruments, confirming seat position, and practising the correct control grip and horizon referencing.
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- Identify the three axes of movement (longitudinal, lateral, normal) and associated planes of motion (roll, pitch, yaw)
- Explain the concept of (dynamic) positive, neutral, and negative stability
- Recall the primary effect of each primary control: elevator — pitch, ailerons — roll, rudder — yaw
- Recall the further effects of ailerons (slip, yaw, spiral tendency) and rudder (skid, roll, spiral tendency)
- Explain the effect of trim: removes aerodynamic control loading; does not change attitude; state the correct direction of input for each force
- Explain the effect of power on pitch and yaw; explain slipstream effect on the tail surfaces
- Explain the effect of airspeed on control effectiveness
- Explain the effect of flaps on lift, drag, pitch, and power requirement
- Identify all documents required to be on board for a legal flight and explain the purpose of each
- Describe the purpose of the maintenance release and what it communicates
- Access NAIPS with own account
- Describe the pre-flight inspection sequence and the purpose of each check area
- Describe safe taxiing technique: power use, brake use, correct wind correction control positions for all wind conditions, prop wash, confined spaces

#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Identify each primary control surface, ancillary control and trim device on the actual aircraft during the walkaround
- Locate and read the maintenance release; identify the key items to check
- Confirm all required documents are present in the aircraft documentation folder
- Complete the pre-flight inspection
- Sit in the cockpit: confirm seat position and locking; hold the controls correctly; identify all instruments

#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [TEM] Identify and verbalise ground operation hazards: propellers, prop wash, confined spaces, other aircraft, wind effects on the ground
- [SA] Demonstrate awareness of the airport environment: runway, taxiways, runup area, wind direction
- [HF] Apply IMSAFE self-assessment and explain the purpose of each item; confirm fitness to fly
- [CRM] Describe the correct control handover procedure: "I have control / you have control"
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- Aircraft Attitude / Axes of Movement *(Pg 101, 102)*
- Primary Flying Controls *(Pg 103–105)*
- Further Effects, spiral tendency, slipstream and speed effects *(Pg 103–107)*
- Lift Augmentation and trim *(Pg 126–131)*
- Aerodynamics — The Basics *(Pg 110–118)*
- Human Factors — IMSAFE, TEM, SA *(Pg 3, 13–16, 45)*
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 90 minutes \
Equipment required: Aircraft, aircraft model, access to electronic briefing, POH, maintenance release, NAIPS access, whiteboard \

*Syllabus Structure, Progression, and Introduction to Flight Training* (10 minutes)
- If the student is under 18, a parent or guardian should attend this portion of the briefing
- Syllabus structure: present an overview of the entire syllabus; show the major milestones and explain the purpose of each
- Emphasise that the entire training programme is competency-based and will most likely require repeating lessons until the required standard is reached
- Depending on the conditions on the day, the student's level of proficiency, and a number of other factors, the lesson order may be adjusted or a planned lesson cancelled
- Grading system: explain the NC, P, S, C grading system and what each means in practice
- Theory exams: the student is expected to self-study (with paid assistance if needed); students will be reminded of upcoming exam requirements; however, it is their responsibility to ensure all exams are completed by the correct stage in training; exams can be taken without booking a flying lesson

*Non-Technical Skills and IMSAFE* (5 minutes)
- IMSAFE: Illness, Medication, Stress, Alcohol, Fatigue, Eating/Drinking — apply before every flight without exception; if any item is a concern, do not fly
- [TEM] Ground operation hazards: propellers (do not walk in front of occupied aircraft, keys visable on the dash, master on only when needed); prop wash; other aircraft taxiing; confined spaces; wind effects on parked and taxiing aircraft
- [SA] Airport layout orientation: parking, runup area, runway, taxiways, windsock, circuit direction; orient the student using the actual aerodrome
- [CRM] Control handover procedure: "I have control/you have control" stated clearly; both occupants confirm on controls before release; "follow me through" technique — feel the input, do not add to it

*Required Documents for Flight* (5 minutes)
- Documents that must be available on board: pilot certificate; aircraft registration; maintenance release (current and signed)
- Documents are checked during the pre-flight sequence and held in the aircraft documentation folder
- If any document is missing: the flight does not proceed; report to CFI

*Aircraft Documentation — Maintenance Release and POH* (5 minutes)
- Purpose: confirms the aircraft has been maintained in accordance with the correct schedule and is authorised for flight
- Key items: last signed date; any required maintainence ouside the schedule; any endorsements; oil entries
- Who signs it: the student reviews all items and briefs the instructor before the instructor signs
- Location of the POH

*NAIPS Introduction* (5 minutes)
- Purpose: official source of aeronautical weather; access via app or web
- TAF: Terminal Aerodrome Forecast; wind, visibility, cloud, significant weather; validity period
- GAF and GPWT: Area forecast; must be used when at an aerodrome without TAF; similar information to TAF, but wider area
- Instructor accesses NAIPS live and walks through the current GAF/GPWT or TAF for the home aerodrome: explain each component
- BOM radar: supplemental tool only; shows precipitation but is not a forecast; not an official source

*Pre-Flight Inspection Walkthrough* (10 minutes)
- Walk the student through the complete pre-flight inspection on the actual aircraft
- Purpose of each check area: fuel quality and quantity; oil level and colour; airframe condition; control surfaces, hinges, and full travel; pitot tube clear; tyres and undercarriage; control locks and covers removed; propeller leading edge condition; cowlings secure; antennas attached; fuel caps secured
- Fuel drain demonstration: drain from all sumps; show correct sample technique; identify water contamination (beads or bubble at bottom) correct colour for fuel type
- Oil: correct quantity and colour; minimum for flight per POH; location of spare oil
- Procedure discipline: do not allow distractions; use the same procedure each time; step back from the aircraft and check the big picture at the end

*Axes and Planes of Movement* (5 minutes)
- Three axes: longitudinal (nose to tail — roll), lateral (wingtip to wingtip — pitch), normal (vertical — yaw)
- Demonstrate on the aircraft model

*Stability* (5 minutes)
- Positive stability: if displaced, eventually returns to the original attitude; will be demonstrated in flight in next lesson
- Neutral stability: if displaced, remains in the new attitude
- Negative stability: if displaced, departs further — no modern training aircraft has negative static or dynamic stability
- Dihedral and swept wings provide lateral stability; tailplane provides longitudinal stability

*Primary Controls* (15 minutes)
- Elevator: primary effect — pitch; further effect — airspeed changes and RPM; demonstrate on model
- Ailerons: primary effect — roll; further effects — slip, yaw then spiral tendency if held; demonstrate on model
- Rudder: primary effect — yaw; further effects — skid, roll then spiral tendency; demonstrate on model
- Emphasis: elevator is the primary airspeed control; throttle is the primary altitude control — this difference from intuition will be reinforced in every lesson

*Ancillary Controls* (15 minutes)
- Trim: removes aerodynamic load on the pilot's controls; does not change the attitude; if holding back-pressure, trim nose-up (thumb); if pushing forward, trim nose-down (finger); demonstrate on the controls when at the actual aircraft
- Power: pitch up with power increase; yaw and roll left with power increase (torque/slipstream); demonstrate on model
- Slipstream: spiralling airflow from the propeller strikes the horizontal stabiliser on one side; causes yaw; corrected with rudder
- Airspeed: controls feel heavier and are more responsive at high speed, feel lighter and are less responsive at low speed
- Flaps: increase lift and drag; nose pitches down on extension; requires more power for level flight; demonstrate flap travel on the actual aircraft

*Safe Taxiing — Theory* (10 minutes)
- Power: use minimum power required to start rolling on a hard surface however; more power needed on soft surfaces
- Surface: do not stop taxiing with the propeller over a loose surface unless absolutely necessary, keep a "walking" pace at all times; if forced to stop, start moving with minimum power required
- Brakes: only used with power idle; used to stop; do not use harsh braking; toe brakes vs hand brakes
- Elevator fully rearwards while taxiing unless in strong winds, then use wind correction position
- Confined spaces and prop wash: keep awareness of wingtip clearance and prop wash
- Speed: taxi at walking pace in the parking area and near other aircraft; slightly faster on open taxiways; faster again when backtracking
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Access NAIPS; obtain GAF/GPWT/TAF for the home aerodrome; demonstrate to student: explain each element, wind, visibility, cloud, validity period
- Create NAIPS account; on the students phone (if able) help them create a NAIPS account
- Review maintenance release; walk student through each section; explain the purpose of each item; sign the release
- Check airfield NOTAMs on the operations whiteboard; brief any relevant items to the student
- Conduct the pre-flight inspection with the student, explaining each check item; encourage questions throughout
- Demonstrate correct entry/exit technique; emphasise tendency to tip onto tail; show safe strong holds

#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Complete IMSAFE self-assessment verbally; confirm fitness to fly
- Observe instructor obtaining and interpreting the GAF/GPWT/TAF
- Observe instructor reviewing the maintenance release; note which sections are completed by the pilot
- Walk through the complete pre-flight inspection with the instructor; identify each item checked; ask about anything not understood
- Locate and confirm all required documents are present in the aircraft folder
- Sit in the cockpit: use correct entry/exit technique; confirm seat position and locking; identify all instruments and controls; practise correct control grip (two fingers and thumb); note instrument positions relative to left-seat view; practise taxi control positions
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
Not applicable — no flight is conducted.

The student sits in the cockpit (engine off) for familiarisation only. Physical taxiing begins in Lesson 1.
]

,common_errors:[
Not applicable
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Student describes what they found most difficult to understand; identifies any theory items that are still unclear.
- *Instructor Review* (10 min):
  - Verbal Q&A: test primary effects, further effects, trim direction, and wind corrections
  - Confirm the student can walk through the pre-flight inspection sequence from memory at a high level
  - Confirm required documents are understood and their purpose is clear
  - Preview Lesson 1: "In the next lesson, we taxi for the first time and then fly. Your job before then is to read the homework so the theory is solid."
- *Next Steps*: Assign homework. The student should be able to recall all primary effects, further effects, and describle trim usage before Lesson 1.
]

,standards_for_progression:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Progressing (P) — may advance to Lesson 1*]
- *Theory*: Names all primary controls and their primary effects without prompting; describes the further effects of ailerons and rudder with minor prompting; states the effect of trim correctly
- *Wind corrections*: States the correct control position for all four wind conditions
- *Pre-flight inspection*: Followed the inspection sequence with the instructor; can describe the purpose of the main check areas
- *Documents*: Confirmed documents present; understands the purpose of each
- *IMSAFE*: Completed and can explain each item

- *Note*: This is a ground lesson — there is no flight standard. The student advances to Lesson 1 when the ground content is understood sufficiently to allow effective use of the first flight. If the student cannot recall basic theory items without lots of prompting, schedule an additional ground session before Lesson 1.

- *Outcome*: Recorded as P (ready for Lesson 1) or NC (requires additional ground session) with specific comments.
]

,safety:[
- *Ground operations*: No engine start, no taxi in this lesson; all aircraft interaction is walkaround and cockpit familiarisation with engine off
- *Propeller awareness*: Brief the student on propeller safety before any approach to the aircraft — non-negotiable from the first contact with the aircraft
- *TEM*: Monitor for student overwhelm — this is a large volume of new information; pace the lesson; check understanding regularly; it is better to take an additional session than to rush
- *No time pressure*: Lesson 0 has no flight; allow the student to ask questions freely; this foundation affects the quality of every subsequent lesson, do not rush this lesson or skip content
]

,homework:[
- Read Bob Tait's RAAus Study Guide:
  - Aircraft Attitude / Axes: Pg 101, 102
  - Primary Controls: Pg 103–105 (primary effects of each control)
  - Further Effects: Pg 105–107 (adverse yaw, spiral tendency, slipstream)
  - Lift Augmentation and Trim: Pg 126–131 (flaps, trim)
  - Aerodynamics Basics: Pg 110–118 (lift, drag, aerofoils)
  - Human Factors: Pg 3, 13–16, 45 (IMSAFE, TEM, SA)
- Practise the pre-flight inspection sequence from memory — attempt to recall the walkthrough from today
- Reflect:
  - "If you apply right aileron, what happens first? What happens next?"
  - "If you are holding back-pressure on the controls, which direction do you move the trim? Why?"
  - "You have a strong quartering tailwind from the right. What aileron and elevator position do you hold during taxi?"
]
)

